            <p>Tangub City is hidden within at the southern curve of the D- shaped province of Misamis Occidental. It is bounded on the north by Mt. Malindang Range, on the south by Panguil Bay, on the east by Ozamiz City and on the west by the municipality of Bonifacio. It is composed of 55 barangays, 23 are urban and 32 are rural.
                The ultimate goal of the City is the improvement of quality of life and its constituents through total human development and where people have equal access to the benefits, opportunities and resources.</p>
            <p>The city’s vision is to become the agribusiness and learning center for skills and technology in Northwestern Mindanao. Its mission is to optimally develop and utilize the city’s human resources by integrating people-centered development to all sectors within the framework of good governance, ecological balance, sound moral values, sustainability and socio-economic development.
            </p><h4>Best time to visit
            </h4><ol><li>1. February – Charter anniversary and inter-collegiate games - A twin event held annually in celebration of the city’s charter day every last week of the month.
                </li><li>2. September 29 – Dalit Festival – a thanksgiving festival to the City’s Patron Saint Michael the Archangel participated by different schools of the city.
                </li><li>3. December – The first day of December is the start of the Christmas Symbols Festival. The festival is a month-long celebration featuring giant Christmas symbols, Christmas arches, giant Christmas lanterns (parols) displayed in the city from November to January. It is an exhibition of Tangubanon ingenuity and creativity.
                </li></ol>

